  <title>GLib.Private</title>
  <synopsis><code>
const GLib = imports.gi.GLib;

let private = new GLib.Private();
  </code></synopsis>
  <p>The <link xref="GLib.Private"/> struct is an opaque data structure to represent a
thread-local data key. It is approximately equivalent to the
pthread_setspecific()/pthread_getspecific() APIs on POSIX and to
TlsSetValue()/TlsGetValue() on Windows.</p>  <p>If you don't already know why you might want this functionality,
then you probably don't need it.</p>  <p><link xref="GLib.Private"/> is a very limited resource (as far as 128 per program,
shared between all libraries). It is also not possible to destroy a
<link xref="GLib.Private"/> after it has been used. As such, it is only ever acceptable
to use <link xref="GLib.Private"/> in static scope, and even then sparingly so.</p>  <p>See G_PRIVATE_INIT() for a couple of examples.</p>  <p>The <link xref="GLib.Private"/> structure should be considered opaque.  It should only
be accessed via the g_private_ functions.</p>

